To create carbon reference tokens, you would need to write smart contracts in a programming language such as Solidity. Smart contracts are self-executing contracts with the terms of the agreement between buyer and seller being directly written into lines of code. The code and the agreements contained therein are stored and replicated on the blockchain network.
To create carbon reference tokens, you would need to first define the desired properties of the tokens. For example, you might specify that each carbon reference token represents one ton of carbon dioxide emissions reduced or offset. You would then need to write code that implements the logic for creating, issuing, and tracking these tokens.
Here is a simple example of how you might create a carbon reference token using Solidity:
```csharp
pragma solidity ^0.6.0;
contract CarbonReferenceToken {
    // Define the token's properties
    string public name;
    string public symbol;
    uint8 public decimals;
    uint public totalSupply;
    // Define the token's owner
    address public owner;
    // Define the token's balances for each address
    mapping(address => uint) public balances;
    // Events for token transfers
    event Transfer(address indexed from, address indexed to, uint value);
    // Constructor function
    constructor() public {
        // Set the token's name
        name = "Carbon Reference Token";
        // Set the token's symbol
        symbol = "CRT";
        // Set the number of decimals
        decimals = 2;
        // Set the total supply of tokens
        totalSupply = 1000000;
        // Set the owner of the contract
        owner = msg.sender;
        // Set the owner's balance to the total supply
        balances[owner] = totalSupply;
    }
    // Function to allow the owner to mint new tokens
    function mint(uint value) public {
        // Only allow the owner to mint new tokens
        require(msg.sender == owner, "Only the owner can mint new tokens");
        // Increase the total supply of tokens
        totalSupply += value;
        // Increase the owner's balance
        balances[owner] += value;
    }
    // Function to allow users to transfer tokens to other addresses
    function transfer(address recipient, uint value) public {
        // Check that the sender has sufficient balance
        require(balances[msg.sender] >= value, "Insufficient balance");
        // Subtract the value from the sender's balance
        balances[msg.sender] -= value;
        // Add the value to the recipient's balance
        balances[recipient] += value;
        // Emit a transfer event
        emit Transfer(msg.sender, recipient, value);
    }
}
```
This is just a basic example, and you may need to include additional functionality or modify the code to fit your specific use case.
